description.narrative: By 2022, key stakeholders have the capacity to engage children and adolescents (girls and boys), parents and community influencers through advocacy, sustained social and behaviour change communication for adolescent empowerment and to prevent child abuse, violence and exploitation, which contributes to Access To Justice, Access To Justice (Covid), Adolescent Empowerment, Adolescent Empowerment (Covid), Cross-Sectoral Communication For Development, Gender Discriminatory Roles And Practices, Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage), Harmful Practices (Fgm/C And Child Marriage) (Covid), Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children (Covid), Social Protection. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: In 13 States, UNICEF in partnership with Government and Civil Society Organisations contributed to translate the commitment for adolescent development and participation, with a focus on ending child marriage (ECM), into action, by reaching 5.4 million adolescent girls and 2.4 million adolescent boys with access to information, services and life skills training; and 33 million parents and community members with social and behaviour change communication (SBCC), to generate awareness on harms of child marriage, parenting skills and adolescent issues. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:10/01/2020
